  "prompt": "How is a chemical equation formed?",
  "response": "A chemical equation is formed by representing a chemical reaction using symbols and formulas to indicate the reactants (the starting substances) and the products (the substances formed). Here are the steps to form a balanced chemical equation:\n\n1. **Identify the Reactants and Products**: Determine which substances are involved in the reaction. Write down the chemical formulas for the reactants and products.\n\n2. **Write the Unbalanced Equation**: Write the reactants on the left side and the products on the right side, separated by an arrow (\u2192) that indicates the direction of the reaction. For example:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Reactants} \\rightarrow \\text{Products}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Balance the Equation**: Ensure that the number of atoms for each element is the same on both sides of the equation. This often involves adjusting the coefficients (the numbers in front of the chemical formulas) to achieve this balance. Here are the basic concepts to follow:\n   - Start with an element that appears in only one reactant and one product.\n   - Adjust the coefficients as needed to balance that element.\n   - Continue this process for all elements, progressively balancing until all are equal on both sides.\n   - Only change the coefficients, not the subscripts in the formulas, as changing subscripts alters the compounds.\n\n4. **Check for Correctness**: After balancing the equation, double-check that the number of atoms for each element is equal on both sides. Additionally, ensure that the charges are balanced if the reaction involves ions.\n\n5. **Indicate States of Matter (optional)**: It's standard practice to include the states of matter for each substance in the equation, such as (s) for solid, (l) for liquid, (g) for gas, and (aq) for aqueous solutions.\n\n### Example\n\nConsider the reaction between hydrogen gas and oxygen gas to form water:\n\n1. **Identify**: The reactants are hydrogen (H\u2082) and oxygen (O\u2082), and the product is water (H\u2082O).\n2. **Unbalanced Equation**: \n   \\[\n   \\text{H}_{2(g)} + \\text{O}_{2(g)} \\rightarrow \\text{H}_{2O}_{(l)}\n   \\]\n3. **Balance**: \n   - There are 2 hydrogen atoms on the left and only 2 on the right, which is fine.\n   - However, there are 2 oxygen atoms on the left and only 1 on the right. Therefore, place a coefficient of 2 in front of H\u2082O:\n   \\[\n   \\text{H}_{2(g)} + \\text{O}_{2(g)} \\rightarrow 2\\text{H}_{2O}_{(l)}\n   \\]\n\n   Now we have:\n   - 2 H in reactants and 4 H in products (still needs balancing),\n   - update hydrogen from 1 to 4\n   - Final equation \n   \\[\n   2\\text{H}_{2(g)} + \\text{O}_{2(g)} \\rightarrow 2\\text{H}_{2O}_{(l)}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Check**: Verify that both sides have 4 H and 2 O.\n\nThe balanced chemical equation for the reaction would be:\n\\[\n2\\text{H}_{2(g)} + \\text{O}_{2(g)} \\rightarrow 2\\text{H}_{2O}_{(l)}\n\\]\n\nThis equation now accurately represents the conservation of mass un the chemical reaction.",
